<p>Amazon added that deploying its new drones would "take time" -- and no, there are still no firm dates for a rollout, even as other services start to deploy limited versions of the same tech.</p><div id="inreadAdPlaceholderOuter"><span id="inreadAdPlaceholderMiddle"><span id="inreadAdPlaceholderInner"><div class="cnGptAlign_HorizontalCentered cnGptNotFullWidthSlot cnGptSlotOuter" id="InreadAd_GptOuter"><div class="cnGptSlotInner" id="InreadAd"><script>GptAdSlots.register('InreadAd', '/5574/uk.n5574.wired/news', {"delaySlot":false,"deleteSlotIfEmpty":true,"sizes":"100x100","containerMinWidthToSizeMap":null,"viewportMinWidthToSizeMap":null,"beforeAdLoadingCallback":null,"onRenderEndedCallback":null,"onJumpinessMinimisedRenderEndedCallback":null,"onSizeChangedCallback":null,"keyValues":{"ismobile":["false"],"istablet":["false"],"pukwrd":["news/article"],"doctype":["Article"],"nodeid":["42985"],"tag_KeywordTags":["amazon","amazon prime air","drones","technology"],"position":["inread"]},"minimiseJumpiness":false});</script></div></div></span></span></div><p>But it did see fit to use its new figurehead Jeremy Clarkson to promote its new hybrid drones, which are ale to switch from vertical to horizontal flight instantly.</p>








