<p>The new-look drones are different to more traditional quadcopters, featuring blades on either side of a central package-carrying fuselage, rather than arranged in a circle around a central motor and battery.</p><p>Currently the Prime Air drone is designed to fly at around 400 feet -- the US Federal Aviation Administration's limit for hobby aircraft.</p><div class="mpuOrSky cnGptMinimiseJumpiness cnGptAlign_HorizontalCentered cnGptNotFullWidthSlot cnGptSlotOuter" data-incontentplaceholderid="incontentAd_last" id="ArticleBottom_GptOuter"><div class="cnGptSlotInner" id="ArticleBottom"><script>GptAdSlots.register('ArticleBottom', '/5574/uk.n5574.wired/news', {"delaySlot":false,"deleteSlotIfEmpty":true,"sizes":null,"containerMinWidthToSizeMap":null,"viewportMinWidthToSizeMap":{"0":",420x160","640":"300x250,300x251,3x3,420x160"},"beforeAdLoadingCallback":null,"onRenderEndedCallback":null,"onJumpinessMinimisedRenderEndedCallback":null,"onSizeChangedCallback":null,"keyValues":{"ismobile":["false"],"istablet":["false"],"pukwrd":["news/article"],"doctype":["Article"],"nodeid":["42985"],"tag_KeywordTags":["amazon","amazon prime air","drones","technology"],"pos":["2"],"position":["article-bottom"]},"minimiseJumpiness":true});</script></div></div><p>UK regulations <a href="http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2015-07/22/civil-aviation-authority-publishes-dronecode-for-drone-owners">would seemingly make a widespread rollout impossible</a> -- drones are required by law to be within the eye-line of pilots and not fly without a license over populated areas. Amazon hopes new regulations can be drawn up to allow their commercial use, though -- as ever -- much arguing, testing and infrastructure improvements will be needed for that to happen.</p><div id="incontentAd_last" class="incontentAd" data-ad-placeholder-state="not-rendered"></div>


		                    

		                    		   

